West ISD “Return to Learn” Safety Tip #8: Always Strive to Social Distance in the Classrooms

With the first day of school coming soon, it’s time to remind all Trojans & Lady Trojans about the importance of social distancing (6 feet) when in classrooms, shared spaces, labs, hallways, and other learning areas.

Now is a good time to talk about how COVID-19 spreads mainly among individuals who are in close contact (within about 6 feet) for a prolonged period. Spread happens when an infected individual coughs, sneezes, or talks, and droplets from their mouth or nose are launched into the air and land in the mouths or noses of people nearby. The droplets can also be inhaled into the lungs.

West ISD has worked hard to reduce the number of students in each classroom through the master schedule, course offerings, removing furniture, purchasing desk shields, relocating some classes to larger spaces, and offering outdoor learning spaces. All students must remember to always wear a face mask and social distance.

Go Healthy & Safe Trojans & Lady Trojans!

West ISD “Return to Learn” Safety Tip #7: Safety FIRST during ALL Transition Times

With the first day of school coming soon, it’s time to remind all Trojans & Lady Trojans about the District’s new safety plans for all transition periods. Whether its arrival, dismissal, or any transition time between classes, West ISD has crafted ways to help keep all students safe as they move around their campuses.

Now is a good time to talk about how West ISD plans to use up and down only staircases, one-way hallways, arrival time combined with an extended Homeroom or Period 1 time, dismissal from the last class period of the day, and limited entry points with Temperature Check stations.

Go Healthy & Safe Trojans & Lady Trojans!

West ISD “Return to Learn” Safety Tip #6: Always Social Distance in the Cafeteria

With the first day of school coming soon, it’s time to remind all Trojans & Lady Trojans about the District’s new cafeteria breakfast and lunch plans. West Elementary School will move to serving all meals in the classroom, and West Middle/High School will now offer breakfast “to go” and have four lunch periods with social distancing at the tables.

Now is a good time to talk about using the online School Bucks website in lieu of bringing cash to the cafeteria lines. Students also should review the new guidelines which restrict the delivery of outside food and shift party goods from homemade to store-bought treats.

Go Healthy & Safe Trojans & Lady Trojans!

West ISD “Return to Learn” Safety Tip #5: Use the Water Bottle Filler over the Fountain

Is it safe to drink from a water fountain during the pandemic? Yes, if you follow West ISD’s Safety Tip #5! With the first day of school coming soon, it’s time to remind all Trojans & Lady Trojans about the advantages of using the water bottle fillers over the water fountains. Though public drinking water supplies are safe to drink, the surfaces around the fountain including the spout, button/leaver and nozzles could pose a risk for the transmission of COVID-19 and other germs. With this news, all West ISD campuses now have water bottle fillers. Yahoo!

Now is a good time to talk about which water bottle you plan to bring to school. There will be time in the day to fill up your favorite bottle (without touching the spout) in order to have water during breaks from learning.

Go Healthy & Safe Trojans & Lady Trojans!

post_text:
West ISD “Return to Learn” Safety Tip #4: Use Hand Sanitizer Whenever Possible

With the first day of school coming soon, it’s time to remind all Trojans & Lady Trojans about the advantages of washing their hands or using hand sanitizer whenever possible.

Now is a good time to talk about how germs are everywhere. Germs can get onto hands and items we touch during daily activities and make us sick. Cleaning hands at key times with soap and water or hand sanitizer is one of the most important steps our students can take to avoid getting sick and spreading germs to those around our buses, classrooms, and schools.

Here are a few reminders when using hand sanitizer: (1) Put enough sanitizer on your hands to cover all surfaces, (2) Rub your hands together until they feel dry (this should take around 20 seconds), and (3) Do NOT rinse or wipe off the hand sanitizer before it is dry; it may not work well against germs.

Go Healthy & Safe Trojans & Lady Trojans!

West ISD “Return to Learn” Safety Tip #1: Wear your Face Mask

With the first day of school coming soon, it’s time to remind all Trojans & Lady Trojans that face masks are required for all students in Grades 3-12 and encouraged at PK-Grade 2 each day from arrival to dismissal time (also during bus rides for all grade levels). Please know that some teachers or students in PK-Grade 2 may request face masks to be worn due to health concerns or medical considerations.

Now is a good time to talk as a family about when and why it is important to have the face mask on, why the face masks cannot be shared, ways to keep the face mask clean, and why the face mask needs to cover the nose and their mouth at the same time.
Also, please consider wearing the face masks for short and long periods of time over the next week as practice for the start of school. Finally, the style and comfort of the face mask and how the straps adjust around the ears all need to be considered before Tuesday, September 8, 2020.

Go Healthy & Safe Trojans & Lady Trojans!

Now is a good time to talk as a family about when and why it is important to have the face mask on, why the face masks cannot be shared, ways to keep the face mask clean, and why the face mask needs to cover the nose and their mouth at the same time.
Also, please consider wearing the face masks for short and long periods of time over the next week as practice for the start of school. Finally, the style and comfort of the face mask and how the straps adjust around the ears all need to be considered before Tuesday, September 8, 2020.

Go Healthy & Safe Trojans & Lady Trojans!

post_text: Go Mr. and Ms. Clark (no relation)! Both great additions to the Pride of West Band program! Welcome to West! Students... don't miss the chance to get to meet them both tomorrow night!
shared_text:
Mark Daniel Dorsey‎Trojan Band - Pride of West
July 13 at 2:36 PM ·

Please join us tomorrow night July 14th 6:00pm, to meet the two new Band Directors here at West, Aubrianne Clark and Austin Clark.

Now I know what some of you are asking yourselves...

Yes they are awesome people who are going to teach here.

But they have the same.....

Yes they have the same passions and drive. To help their students be as awesome as they can be.

I have emailed all current band students and parents the link to the google hangout tomorrow. Students please use your West ISD email to login. I hope to see you all there. These two people are excited to get to see everyone and ready to started!!

post_text:
Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) Information:

The USDA and Texas Government are offering a new program to help our most vulnerable families during this crisis. Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to our school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from West ISD tomorrow, Friday, May 29, 2020, via Skyward School Messenger, and the application will open the first week of June.

Note: P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, please visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

shared_text:
West ISD TSA
March 31 at 8:08 PM ·

TSA just released the scores for TEAMS (Tests of Engineering Aptitude, Mathematics and Science) state rankings. West placed 15th in multiple choice, 5th in essay and 1st in Design and Build. This led to a 3rd place finish in the state for West High School (1st place was McKinney HS and 2nd place was The Hockaday School).

The team consisted of Colton Meurer, Madison Nichols, Rachel Coffer, Taylor Mynar, Hailey Routson, Kaylin Gerik, Jesse Corvin, and Alec Roessler. We are so proud of our students!

#TexasTSA #OneTSA #InspireASharedVision

post_text: West ISD is preparing a FAQ on the recent STAAR testing cancellation plan by the state. Here is one question with the answer that has been emailed to Mr. Truitt.
shared_text:
Texas Association of School Boards
March 20 at 10:46 AM ·

Will students advance to the next grade without state assessments?

Yes, Gov. Abbott and TEA commissioner Mike Morath answered at a Town Hall held last night. They have empowered districts to make the decisions that are best for their students. They want to ensure students are learning and progressing, and maintain high expectations, but STAAR has been removed from consideration.

“These are unique times that call for unique solutions. We are going to be flexible in delivering solutions that work in our society,” said Gov. Abbott. High school seniors can graduate without taking the STAAR test, as long as they’ve met the academic standards of their local district.

Will students advance to the next grade without state assessments?

Yes, Gov. Abbott and TEA commissioner Mike Morath answered at a Town Hall held last night. They have empowered districts to make the decisions that are best for their students. They want to ensure students are learning and progressing, and maintain high expectations, but STAAR has been removed from consideration.

“These are unique times that call for unique solutions. We are going to be flexible in delivering solutions that work in our society,” said Gov. Abbott. High school seniors can graduate without taking the STAAR test, as long as they’ve met the academic standards of their local district.

post_text: FYI: Juvenile Curfew Information
shared_text:
City of West Police Department
March 17 at 4:15 PM ·

JUVENILE CURFEW - The West City council has reinstated the Juvenile Curfew for the City of West. Effective immediately the hours of the curfew have changed. Juveniles that are 16 years old or younger cannot be out in public places in the City of West after 9pm and until 6am.
The West Police Department will continue to use a common sense approach to this. If a juvenile is traveling to or from work, and can verify place of employment, they will not be cited. Also, if they are with a parent or guardian no action will be taken. The hours of the City of West Juvenile Curfew will remain in effect until further notice from the city council.
text:

March 17 at 4:15 PM ·

JUVENILE CURFEW - The West City council has reinstated the Juvenile Curfew for the City of West. Effective immediately the hours of the curfew have changed. Juveniles that are 16 years old or younger cannot be out in public places in the City of West after 9pm and until 6am.
The West Police Department will continue to use a common sense approach to this. If a juvenile is traveling to or from work, and can verify place of employment, they will not be cited. Also, if they are with a parent or guardian no action will be taken. The hours of the City of West Juvenile Curfew will remain in effect until further notice from the city council.

post_text:
Gabe's Groupies News for Tonight's Basketball Games!

Please join the West High School Cheerleaders in their annual fundraiser for Cystic Fibrosis--Gabe's Groupies on Tuesday, January 28, 2020, during the Varsity Girls and Boys Basketball games. The games will start at 6:00 PM. There will be activities such as a Silent Auction, 50/50 Raffle, Wall of Money donation board, Pass the Megaphone, and Tortilla Toss. The fun part of the night is when a West High School teacher who raises the most money will take a pie in the face from Gabe Lauer during half-time of the Boys Basketball game.

Come out and support the Cystic Fibrosis Foundation and the West High Cheerleaders!

post_text: Thank you Officer Keathley!
shared_text:
City of West Police Department is feeling proud in City of West.
January 23 at 3:29 PM · West, TX ·

WISD "FRIEND OF WEST" - During the West ISD School Board Meeting on January 8th, 2020 Police Officer Michael Keathley was recognized as a "Friend of West" Honoree. Superintendent David Truitt gave this as recognition of Officer Keathley's dedicated service as the School Resource Officer (SRO) for the last 5 years.

Officer Keathley was also recognized at the West Police Awards Banquet in December for his service as SRO as well as Code Enforcement Officer and 5 years with West PD. Congratulations Officer Michael Keathley on your recent recognitions.

post_text: Helping Hands is looking for hygiene items for our students in need. Thank you for your consideration!
shared_text:
Becca Matus
January 20 at 6:52 PM ·

Okay friends, I'm collecting the goods again.

West ISD's Helping Hands is needing items for hygiene packs. They send home toothbrushes, soaps, deodorant, etc with students who may not have access to those items at home.

They are currently stocked on toothbrushes and toothpaste but need the following in travel sizes:
- body wash/bar soap
- deodorant
- razors
- shampoo/conditioner
- feminine hygiene products

You can get items to me or directly to someone with Helping Hands if you have anything to donate.
Thanks a bunch!
